Europe
------
[1] UK (England, Sussex)
Date: Sun 18 Dec 2011
Source: The Argus [edited]
http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/9425629.Hopes_Christmas_break_will_ease_Brighton_and_Hove_measles_outbreak/

Hope that Christmas break will ease Brighton and Hove measles
outbreak
-------
The festive break could help slow a measles outbreak in Brighton and
Hove [in the county of Sussex]. Health bosses are battling to contain
the spread of the virus, which has hit more than 40 people so far this
year. There were 19 new cases confirmed in November and a further
three this month [December]. The actual number is expected to be
higher as tests are being carried out on another 18 samples. Many of
those infected are schoolchildren, who have now broken up [gone home]
for the Christmas holidays. It is hoped the break away from the
enclosed environment of a classroom may reduce the risk of more cases
emerging.

The city's director of public health, Tom Scanlon, said: “We had a
spike in cases in November and we would have liked to see that rate
slowing down more quickly, but it hasn't really been happening yet.
“Hopefully, the Christmas break will help. It just goes to show the
large number of unvaccinated people there are in the city.”

Brighton and Hove has one of the lowest [vaccine] take-up rates for
the measles, mumps and rubella vaccine in the South East. Many parents
were put off the vaccine because of the, now discredited, link between
it and autism. The rate currently stands at more than 80% but this is
nowhere near the 95% recommended by the World Health Organisation as
needed to protect a community. "We are experiencing these cases after
a break last year. This pattern is likely to continue until we can get
those vaccination rates up.” MMR vaccines are normally given at
around the ages of two and five, but they can still be given if a
child is older.

(By Siobhan Ryan)

